<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to the Phillips Curve when there is a favorable supply shock?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The curve shifts outward showing higher inflation at all unemployment rates</option>
            <option letter="b">The curve shifts inward showing lower inflation at all unemployment rates</option>
            <option letter="c">The curve becomes steeper showing a stronger trade-off</option>
            <option letter="d">The curve becomes more vertical showing no trade-off</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>A favorable supply shock (like lower oil prices or improved technology) shifts the Phillips Curve inward. This means the economy can achieve lower inflation rates at any given unemployment rate, representing an improved trade-off between inflation and unemployment.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
